АУDeceased","1190вАУFemale":"1190вАУDeceased","1190":"1190","Abt 1240":"about 1240","1267":"1267","1200":"1200","1265":"1265","1220":"1220","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","Tolleshunt, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Essex, England, United Kingdom","Knights, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Essex, England, United Kingdom","Coleshill, Warwickshire, England":"Coleshill, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hillary","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names ¬© Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Caitlin, Ciaran.","English (of Norman origin):","from the Middle English and Old French male or female personal name <i>Hilari(e)</i>, <i>Ilari(e)</i>, and <i>Elari(e)</i>, from Latin <i>Hilarius</i> and <i>Hilaria</i> вАШjoyfulвАЩ (from Greek <i>hilaros</i>). The Latin name was chosen by many early Christians to express their joy and hope of salvation, and was borne by several saints, including a 4th-century bishop of Poitiers (died 368) noted for his vigorous resistance to the Arian heresy, and a 5th-century bishop of Arles. Largely due to veneration of Saint Hilarius of Poitiers, the name became popular in France in the forms <i>Hilari</i> and <i>Hilaire</i>, and was brought to England by the Norman conquerors. Although quite popular in France, it was only occasionally used in England, where it was confused with the name in 2 below."],"variants":[{"name":"Ellery","meanings":["variant of   Hillary  .","habitational name from Elleray in Windermere (Westmorland), probably from Old Norse <i>elri</i> вАШalderвАЩ + <i>vr√°</i> вАШnookвАЩ.","English:"]},{"name":"Gloor","meanings":["Swiss German: from a vernacular form of the Latin personal name <i>Hilarius</i> (see   Hillary  )."]},{"name":"Hillier","meanings":["English (Wiltshire and Surrey): occupational name for a roofer from Middle English <i>hil(l)ier</i>, <i>hul(li)er</i>, <i>hel(li)er</i> вАШroofer, slater, tilerвАЩ, agent nouns from the Middle English verb <i>hil(i)en</i>, <i>hel(i)an</i>, <i>hul(i)en</i> вАШto put a roof on; cover with a roofвАЩ.","French: from the personal name <i>Hillier</i>, a vernacular form of <i>Hilaire</i> (see   Hillary  )."]},{"name":"Alario","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Orazio, Carlo, Rocco, Salvatore, Vita, Vitina.","Italian: from a vernacular form of the personal name <i>Ilario</i>, from Latin <i>Hilarius</i> (see   Hillary  ).","Italian (Sicily): probably a status name from dialect <i>alariu</i> вАШheraldвАЩ."]},{"name":"Glor","meanings":["German: from a vernacular form of the Latin personal name <i>Hilarius</i> (see   Hillary  )."]},{"name":"Hillery","meanings":["English: variant of   Hillary  . This name has long been established in Ireland (Clare)."]},{"name":"Hilaire","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Jacques, Pierre, Antoine, Chantal, Edeline, Georges, Luc, Maryse, Mimose, Serge, Yolaine.","French and West Indian (mainly Haiti): from the personal name <i>Hilaire</i>, French form of   Hillary   1. This surname is most common in Haiti. Compare   Helaire  ."]},{"name":"Hilleary","meanings":["English (Essex): variant of   Hillary  . This form of the surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Allaire","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Normand, Andre, Lucien, Alphonse, Antoine, Armand, Emile, Michel, Pierre, Raoul, Raymonde, Rolande.","French: from the Old French personal name <i>Allaire</i>, a variant of <i>Hilaire</i> (see   Hillary  ). Compare   Dallaire  .","History: Jean and Charles Allaire, two brothers from the Poitou region of France, are recorded in Quebec City, QC, in 1662 and 1663, respectively, the years of their marriage. The descendants of one or another brother also bear altered forms of the surname, such as <i>Dallaire</i>, <i>Delair</i>, and <i>Delaire</i>. вАФ Alexandre Allaire, a Huguenot refugee, brought the name from La Rochelle in France to New Rochelle, NY, in 1686, via the West Indies. He is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of America."]},{"name":"Hilario","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Julio, Alfredo, Luis, Abelardo, Arturo, Eduardo, Francisco, Juan, Mario, Pedro, Carlos, Cesar.  Portuguese Afonso, Joao.","Portuguese (<b>Hil√°rio</b>) and Spanish: from a personal name ofthe same origin as   Hillary   1."]}]},{"name":"Elizabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names ¬© Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533вАУ1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900вАУ2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means вАШGod is my oathвАЩ, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbƒБth</i> вАШSabbathвАЩ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Elizabeth Hillary was born in 1220, in Essex, England, United Kingdom, her father, Hillary, was 30 and her mother, Mrs Hillary, was 30. She had at least 1 son with William de la Plaunche Fiennes. She died in 1260, in her hometown, at the age of 40."},"et":{"1220вАУ1260":"